Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

# PCA with scaling
pr.out=prcomp(USArrests, scale=TRUE) # put the variables in the same scale
names(pr.out) # Five components
## [1] "sdev"     "rotation" "center"   "scale"    "x"
pr.out$center # the centering and scaling used (means)
##   Murder  Assault UrbanPop     Rape 
##    7.788  170.760   65.540   21.232
pr.out$scale # the matrix of variable loadings (eigenvectors)
##    Murder   Assault  UrbanPop      Rape 
##  4.355510 83.337661 14.474763  9.366385
pr.out$rotation
##                 PC1        PC2        PC3         PC4
## Murder   -0.5358995  0.4181809 -0.3412327  0.64922780
## Assault  -0.5831836  0.1879856 -0.2681484 -0.74340748
## UrbanPop -0.2781909 -0.8728062 -0.3780158  0.13387773
## Rape     -0.5434321 -0.1673186  0.8177779  0.08902432
dim(pr.out$x)
## [1] 50  4
pr.out$rotation=-pr.out$rotation 
pr.out$x=-pr.out$x
biplot(pr.out, scale=0)

# to just plot PC3 and PC4
biplot(pr.out, choices = 3:4, scale=0)

#first 2 components make more sense, 
biplot(pr.out, choices = 1:2, scale=0)
